  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Sacrificial Offering to King Kangjon
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, how sorrowful. The virtue etched upon your being surpassed even the sage-kings of old—worthy of Yao's longevity, yet you departed this realm. Your vigilant heart exceeded even King Wen of Zhou, and we believed you would inherit his celestial mandate. How could you abandon the throne of ten thousand chariots without securing the blessings of a thousand years? Has the world grown distant from virtue? Does goodness leave no trace?

    I lament my own unworthiness. As a son, I have been deficient—dwelling in a distant lodge, unable to attend at your chamber door. Who could have foreseen that illness would suddenly claim you? There was no time for warning. These hands never prepared your medicine; these ears never heard your final words. O endless sorrow—when shall this anguish ever cease?

    All mortals know the grief of losing a father, yet who has endured a pain like mine? The white crane came to bear you away without a moment's delay. The dragon's whisker, once so vital, is now forever severed—how shall I grasp it again? The sun darkens in the highest heavens. The sky crumbles over ten thousand nations. Is this real or illusion? Waking or dream? My mind reels in confusion.

    Calling out, weeping, remembering, yearning—yet none of this allows me to see your face once more. I can only harbor boundless longing. With this humble libation, I humbly offer it to your spirit. Accept this meager draught, and grant solace to this shattered heart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yao and King Wen of Zhou are legendary sage-rulers in Chinese philosophy, representing the ideal of virtuous governance and celestial blessing.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'white crane' and 'dragon's whisker' are classical metaphors for death and the severing of life's vital connection.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'ten thousand chariots' (万乘) symbolizes imperial power and sovereignty.
